Here are the installation steps and documentation for Visual Studio Code, Git CLI, and Databricks CLI for both Mac and Windows operating systems:

1. Visual Studio Code
For macOS
Download VS Code:

Visit the official Visual Studio Code website.
Download the .zip file for macOS.
Install VS Code:

Open the downloaded .zip file and drag the Visual Studio Code.app file to the Applications folder.
Launch VS Code:

Open Launchpad or the Applications folder and double-click Visual Studio Code.
Optional: Add VS Code to PATH:

Open VS Code.
Press Cmd+Shift+P to open the Command Palette.
Type Shell Command: Install 'code' command in PATH and press Enter.
Install Extensions:

Open VS Code.
Go to the Extensions Marketplace (Cmd+Shift+X).
Search for and install extensions like Python, GitLens, or Prettier.
For Windows
Download VS Code:

Visit the official Visual Studio Code website.
Download the .exe installer for Windows.
Install VS Code:

Run the downloaded .exe file.
Follow the prompts to accept the license agreement.
Select installation options like:
Add to PATH (recommended).
Create a desktop shortcut.
Launch VS Code:

Open it from the Start menu or desktop shortcut.
Install Extensions:

Open the Extensions Marketplace (Ctrl+Shift+X).
Search and install extensions like Python, GitLens, or Prettier.
2. Git CLI
For macOS
Install Git:

Open a terminal and type:
bash
Copy code
git --version
If Git is not installed, macOS will prompt you to install the Xcode Command Line Tools. Accept the prompt to install Git.
Optional: Install Git via Homebrew:

Install Homebrew if you haven't already:
bash
Copy code
/bin/bash -c "$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebrew/install/HEAD/install.sh)"
Use Homebrew to install Git:
bash
Copy code
brew install git
Verify Installation:

Check the Git version:
bash
Copy code
git --version
Configure Git:

Set your name and email:
bash
Copy code
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "youremail@example.com"
For Windows
Download Git:

Visit the Git website and download the installer for Windows.
Install Git:

Run the downloaded .exe file.
During installation:
Select the default options unless you have specific preferences.
Choose the default editor for Git (e.g., VS Code).
Opt to "Use Git from the command line and also from 3rd-party software."
Launch Git Bash:

Open Git Bash (installed by default) from the Start menu for a Linux-like shell.
Verify Installation:

Open a terminal (Command Prompt or Git Bash) and type:
bash
Copy code
git --version
Configure Git:

Set your name and email:
bash
Copy code
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "youremail@example.com"
3. Databricks CLI
For macOS
Install Python:

Ensure Python 3.7 or later is installed.
Verify by typing:
bash
Copy code
python3 --version
If not installed, use Homebrew:
bash
Copy code
brew install python
Install Databricks CLI:

Use pip to install the Databricks CLI:
bash
Copy code
pip3 install databricks-cli
Verify Installation:

Check the Databricks CLI version:
bash
Copy code
databricks --version
Authenticate Databricks CLI:

Generate a personal access token from Databricks Workspace:
Go to User Settings → Access Tokens → Generate Token.
Configure the CLI:
bash
Copy code
databricks configure --token
Enter the Databricks Host (e.g., https://<workspace>.cloud.databricks.com) and the token.
For Windows
Install Python:

Download Python from the official website.
Install Python and ensure the "Add Python to PATH" option is selected during installation.
Install Databricks CLI:

Use pip to install the Databricks CLI:
bash
Copy code
pip install databricks-cli
Verify Installation:

Check the Databricks CLI version:
bash
Copy code
databricks --version
Authenticate Databricks CLI:

Generate a personal access token from Databricks Workspace:
Go to User Settings → Access Tokens → Generate Token.
Configure the CLI:
bash
Copy code
databricks configure --token
Enter the Databricks Host (e.g., https://<workspace>.cloud.databricks.com) and the token.
Common Commands
Visual Studio Code
Open a folder or file:
bash
Copy code
code <folder_or_file_name>
Install extensions: Use the Extensions Marketplace in VS Code.
Git CLI
Clone a repository:
bash
Copy code
git clone <repository_url>
Check repository status:
bash
Copy code
git status
Add files to staging:
bash
Copy code
git add .
Commit changes:
bash
Copy code
git commit -m "Commit message"
Push changes:
bash
Copy code
git push
Databricks CLI
List clusters:
bash
Copy code
databricks clusters list
List jobs:
bash
Copy code
databricks jobs list
Run a job:
bash
Copy code
databricks jobs run-now --job-id <job-id>
Let me know if you need further clarifications!













